{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Go to `https://git-scm.com/downloads` in your web browser. The page should detect your operating system and show download options for Windows, macOS, and Linux.",
      "title": "Open the Git downloads page"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the download button for your operating system. Your browser should start downloading the installer file automatically.",
      "title": "Download the installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the downloaded Git installer file from your browser's downloads bar or Downloads folder. An installation window should appear.",
      "title": "Launch the installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Next** on each setup screen to keep the default options. The installer should move forward until you reach the final install screen.",
      "title": "Accept the default settings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Install** to begin the installation. Wait until the progress bar finishes and the installer shows a completion screen.",
      "title": "Start the installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Finish** to close the installer. Git is installed when the setup window closes without an error message.",
      "title": "Finish setup"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open Terminal on macOS or Linux, or Git Bash on Windows. You should see a command prompt ready for typing.",
      "title": "Open a command line"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. The command succeeds when you see a version like `git version 2.x.x`.",
      "title": "Verify the Git installation"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Park on firm, level ground away from traffic. Turn on hazard lights and set the parking brake. You should feel the car stay still when you gently release the brake pedal.",
      "title": "Park Safely"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place wheel wedges or heavy objects against the tire opposite the flat. The vehicle should no longer roll when you lightly push it.",
      "title": "Chock the Opposite Wheel"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take out the jack, lug wrench, and spare-tire tools from your trunk or storage area. Check that each tool is within reach before you continue.",
      "title": "Get the Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the hubcap or wheel cover if it blocks the lug nuts. Use the flat end of the lug wrench if needed. You should see all lug nuts clearly.",
      "title": "Remove the Wheel Cover"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn each lug nut counterclockwise about a quarter turn while the tire is still on the ground. If a nut is stuck, press down on the wrench carefully. The nuts should loosen but stay on.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the jacking point nearest the flat tire in your owner's manual or on the vehicle frame. You should see a reinforced metal spot made for the jack.",
      "title": "Locate the Jack Point"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the jack directly under the marked jacking point. Make sure it sits flat and centered. The jack should touch the frame without leaning.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Raise the vehicle until the flat tire is about 2 inches off the ground. Stop if the car shifts or the jack tilts. The tire should spin freely by hand.",
      "title": "Lift the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unscrew the loosened lug nuts completely and place them together in a safe spot. You should have all lug nuts removed before pulling on the wheel.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull the flat tire straight toward you and off the wheel studs. If it sticks, wiggle it gently. The wheel should slide free without the vehicle moving.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place your French press, kettle, coffee, grinder, scale, spoon, and mug on the counter. You should be able to reach everything without leaving your spot.",
      "title": "Gather your tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Put the empty French press on the scale and press tare so the display reads `0`. If it does not reset, press tare again.",
      "title": "Tare the scale"
    },
    {
      "text": "Weigh `30 g` of whole coffee beans on the scale. Stop when the display shows `30 g`, within about `1 g`.",
      "title": "Measure the beans"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grind the beans to a coarse texture, like breadcrumbs. The grounds should look chunky, not powdery. If they look fine, adjust coarser and grind again.",
      "title": "Grind the coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Heat water to about `200°F` or just off the boil. If you do not have a thermometer, let boiling water sit for about 30 seconds.",
      "title": "Heat the water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the ground coffee into the empty French press. The grounds should sit evenly across the bottom.",
      "title": "Add grounds to press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour `500 g` of hot water into the French press. Stop when the scale reads `500 g`. All grounds should look wet.",
      "title": "Add hot water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stir the coffee once with a spoon to wet any floating grounds. You should see the dry clumps disappear.",
      "title": "Stir once"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set a timer for `4` minutes. Start timing as soon as the water is added so your brew stays consistent.",
      "title": "Start a 4-minute timer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the lid on the French press with the plunger pulled all the way up. The filter should rest above the coffee, not pushed down yet.",
      "title": "Set the lid on top"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the plunger down slowly and steadily when the timer ends. Stop at the bottom. If it resists hard, press even more slowly.",
      "title": "Plunge slowly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee into your mug right away. The cup should fill smoothly with little sediment, and the coffee is ready to drink.",
      "title": "Pour and serve"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Clear the garden bed of weeds, rocks, and old roots. Pull out anything growing in the space so only bare soil remains. You should be able to see the full bed surface clearly.",
      "title": "Clear the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2–3 inch layer of compost over the entire bed. Cover the soil evenly from edge to edge. When finished, the surface should look uniformly dark and covered.",
      "title": "Add Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Loosen the soil with a garden fork or shovel to a depth of 8–12 inches. Work across the whole bed. The soil should break apart instead of staying packed in hard chunks.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mix the compost into the loosened soil using your fork or shovel. Blend until the added material is no longer sitting in a separate top layer. The bed should look evenly combined.",
      "title": "Mix in the Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sprinkle a balanced garden fertilizer according to the label rate across the bed. Distribute it as evenly as possible. You should not see thick piles in any one spot.",
      "title": "Apply Fertilizer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rake the bed surface smooth and level. Break up any large clods as you rake. The top should feel even and crumbly, with no deep holes or raised mounds.",
      "title": "Rake the Bed Smooth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Water the prepared bed until the soil is evenly moist but not muddy. Check by squeezing a handful: it should hold together lightly, then crumble when touched.",
      "title": "Moisten the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Let the bed rest for 24 hours before planting tomatoes. After resting, the soil should still feel loose and slightly damp, which means the bed is ready to plant.",
      "title": "Let the Bed Rest"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place your pillowcase pattern, fabric, measuring tape, straight pins, fabric scissors, and chalk on a flat table. You should have enough space to spread the fabric without it hanging over the edge.",
      "title": "Gather your tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the fabric flat on the table with the wrong side facing up. Smooth it with your hands until there are no wrinkles. The fabric should lie flat without bunching or folds.",
      "title": "Lay out the fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fold the fabric as the pattern directs, matching the selvage edges evenly. Align the edges carefully. You should see the fold lying straight with the fabric layers stacked neatly.",
      "title": "Fold the fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the pillowcase pattern pieces on the folded fabric in the layout shown on the pattern. Keep each piece flat. The pattern should fit fully on the fabric without overlapping the edge.",
      "title": "Set the pattern pieces"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure the distance from each pattern piece to the fabric fold or edge where marked. Adjust the piece until the spacing matches the pattern. The measurements should match on both ends.",
      "title": "Measure the placement"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pin through the pattern and fabric around the edges of each piece. Space pins a few inches apart and keep them inside the cutting line. The pattern should stay still when you touch it.",
      "title": "Pin the pattern"
    },
    {
      "text": "Trace around the cutting line with chalk only if your pattern directs you to mark it. Follow the line closely. You should see a clear outline that stays visible when you lift the edge slightly.",
      "title": "Mark the cutting line"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut along the pattern edge or chalk line with fabric scissors. Use long, smooth cuts and keep the fabric flat. The cut edge should look clean and match the pattern shape without jagged spots.",
      "title": "Cut the fabric pieces"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lift the cut pieces and compare them to the pattern shapes and sizes. Check that all edges are complete and smooth. You should have every pillowcase piece needed, ready for sewing.",
      "title": "Check the cut pieces"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Hold your guitar in playing position and have a clip-on tuner, tuning app, or reference pitch ready. You should be able to pluck one string at a time without bumping the others.",
      "title": "Get your guitar ready"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn on your tuner or open your tuning app. If it has instrument options, choose **Guitar**. You should see a note name display and a meter or needle waiting for input.",
      "title": "Open the tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string by itself. Watch the tuner until it settles on a note name. If it jumps around, pluck more gently and mute the other strings with your picking hand.",
      "title": "Play the low E string"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn that string’s tuning peg slowly until the tuner shows `E`. Stop when the needle is centered or the indicator turns green. If the pitch rises the wrong way, turn the peg the other direction.",
      "title": "Tune to low E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the next thickest string by itself and let the tuner settle. You should see the note readout lock more clearly if the other strings stay muted.",
      "title": "Play the A string"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn that string’s peg until the tuner shows `A` and the pitch is centered. Stop as soon as it reads in tune. If you pass `A`, turn back slowly and check again.",
      "title": "Tune to A"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the next string by itself and watch the display settle on a note. This is the middle lower string, between A and G.",
      "title": "Play the D string"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn that string’s peg until the tuner shows `D`. Confirm success when the meter centers or the in-tune light appears.",
      "title": "Tune to D"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the next string by itself and wait for the note reading to steady. If the tuner reads a nearby note, keep the string ringing briefly so it can settle.",
      "title": "Play the G string"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn that string’s peg until the tuner shows `G`. Stop when the display shows in tune, not sharp or flat.",
      "title": "Tune to G"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the second thinnest string by itself and check the tuner display. You should see the note name respond quickly if you pluck near the sound hole.",
      "title": "Play the B string"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn that string’s peg until the tuner shows `B` and the indicator centers. Make small adjustments here, since thinner strings change pitch quickly.",
      "title": "Tune to B"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string by itself and let the tuner settle on a note name. If it sounds very high or very loose, adjust slowly.",
      "title": "Play the high E string"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn that string’s peg until the tuner shows `E` and the meter centers. Confirm it is the higher `E`, not the thick low string.",
      "title": "Tune to high E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck all six strings one at a time again in order: `E A D G B E`. Retune any string that drifted. You’re done when each string shows the correct note and centers in tune.",
      "title": "Check all strings again"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Point your camera at the scene you want to photograph. Keep the framing steady so the exposure reading reflects the actual shot. You should see the scene clearly on the screen or through the viewfinder.",
      "title": "Frame Your Scene"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the mode dial to `M` for Manual mode. This lets you adjust ISO, aperture, and shutter speed yourself. You should see `M` on the top screen or in the viewfinder.",
      "title": "Set Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the `ISO` button or open the ISO setting in your quick menu. The ISO value should become highlighted so you can change it.",
      "title": "Open ISO Setting"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the main dial to choose a starting ISO such as `100` or `200`. Use the lowest value that fits your light. You should see the new ISO number update on screen.",
      "title": "Choose ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the control dial for aperture and select an `f` value. Start near `f/5.6` for a balanced exposure. You should see the aperture display change, such as from `f/4` to `f/5.6`.",
      "title": "Set Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the shutter speed dial or command wheel to set a starting speed like `1/125`. The shutter value should update in the display as you turn the control.",
      "title": "Set Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Half-press the shutter button and look at the exposure meter. Aim to place the marker near `0`. If it stays left or right, the scene is underexposed or overexposed.",
      "title": "Check Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slow the shutter speed or open the aperture if the meter is below `0`. Watch the meter move toward center. If your image preview brightens, you're correcting underexposure.",
      "title": "Brighten the Exposure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Raise the shutter speed, close the aperture, or lower ISO if the meter is above `0`. Watch the marker move toward center. The preview should look less bright as exposure improves.",
      "title": "Darken the Exposure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a test photo and review it on the rear screen. Check that highlights are not blown out and shadows still show detail. If it looks balanced, your exposure is set.",
      "title": "Capture and Confirm"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with your feet about shoulder-width apart on a flat surface. Point your toes slightly outward. You should feel balanced with your weight spread evenly across both feet.",
      "title": "Set your stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold your arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height. This helps you balance. You should be able to keep your chest lifted without leaning back.",
      "title": "Raise your arms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Brace your core by tightening your stomach like you're preparing for a light punch. Keep your ribs down. You should feel your trunk firm up without holding your breath.",
      "title": "Brace your core"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your hips back as if reaching for a chair behind you. Keep your heels down. You should feel your weight stay over your mid-foot, not shift onto your toes.",
      "title": "Send hips back"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bend your knees to lower into the squat. Let your knees track in line with your toes. You should see your chest stay up and your heels remain flat on the floor.",
      "title": "Lower into the squat"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pause at the bottom when your thighs are about parallel to the floor, or as low as you can go with control. You should still keep your back neutral, not rounded.",
      "title": "Pause at the bottom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press through your whole foot to stand back up. Squeeze your glutes at the top. You should return to a tall standing position without your heels lifting.",
      "title": "Stand back up"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your finish in a mirror or window reflection. Your feet should stay planted, knees should follow your toes, and your spine should look neutral from start to finish.",
      "title": "Verify your form"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe farinha de trigo, fermento biológico, água morna, açúcar, sal, óleo ou manteiga e uma tigela grande. Deixe tudo à mão. Você deve conseguir alcançar todos os ingredientes sem sair do lugar.",
      "title": "Separe os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje a água morna na tigela. Ela deve estar morna ao toque, não quente. Se estiver muito quente, espere esfriar para não prejudicar o fermento.",
      "title": "Coloque a água na tigela"
    },
    {
      "text": "Adicione o fermento biológico à água morna. Mexa só o suficiente para umedecer todo o fermento. Você não deve ver partes secas na superfície.",
      "title": "Adicione o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Misture o açúcar na tigela. Quando dissolver, o líquido fica uniforme. Se ainda vir grãos no fundo, mexa mais alguns segundos.",
      "title": "Acrescente o açúcar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Espere 5 a 10 minutos. No fim, a mistura deve ficar espumosa ou com bolhas na superfície. Se nada acontecer, recomece com outro fermento.",
      "title": "Aguarde ativar o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Junte o óleo ou a manteiga derretida à mistura. O líquido deve ficar brilhante e homogêneo. Se a manteiga endurecer, use líquido menos frio na próxima vez.",
      "title": "Adicione a gordura"
    },
    {
      "text": "Acrescente o sal à tigela. Mexa brevemente para distribuir. Você não deve ver sal acumulado em um único ponto da mistura.",
      "title": "Adicione o sal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloque parte da farinha na tigela. Mexa até formar uma massa grossa. Você deve sentir resistência na colher e ver menos líquido solto.",
      "title": "Adicione a primeira farinha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Acrescente mais farinha aos poucos. Pare quando a massa estiver unida e desgrudando das laterais, mas ainda levemente macia ao toque.",
      "title": "Adicione o restante da farinha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Transfira a massa para uma bancada limpa e enfarinhada. Ela deve sair da tigela em um bloco só; se grudar demais, polvilhe um pouco mais de farinha.",
      "title": "Leve a massa à bancada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sove a massa empurrando com a palma da mão. Ela deve começar a ficar mais lisa após alguns movimentos. Se rasgar muito, deixe descansar 2 minutos.",
      "title": "Empurre a massa com a palma"
    },
    {
      "text": "Dobre a massa sobre ela mesma. A dobra deve cobrir o centro e deixar a massa mais compacta para o próximo movimento.",
      "title": "Dobre a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gire a massa um quarto de volta. Isso ajuda a sovar por igual. Você deve notar que o formato continua arredondado e fácil de trabalhar.",
      "title": "Gire a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Repita a sova por 8 a 10 minutos. No final, a massa deve ficar lisa, elástica e voltar levemente quando você pressionar com um dedo.",
      "title": "Repita até ficar lisa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa em uma bola. A superfície deve ficar mais tensa e uniforme, com poucas rachaduras aparentes.",
      "title": "Forme uma bola"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloque a massa em uma tigela levemente untada. Ela deve entrar sem grudar nas laterais. Agora a massa está pronta para descansar.",
      "title": "Passe para a tigela"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Reúne una llave ajustable, desarmador, pinzas, trapo, tapón para el desagüe y las piezas de repuesto del grifo. Debes tener todo al alcance antes de empezar.",
      "title": "Reúne las herramientas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ubica las válvulas de cierre bajo el lavabo y gíralas a la derecha hasta el tope. Si no las ves, usa la llave general. El flujo debe quedar cortado.",
      "title": "Cierra el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre el grifo por completo para vaciar el agua restante en la línea. Debe dejar de salir agua en pocos segundos; si sigue saliendo, revisa las válvulas.",
      "title": "Abre el grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca el tapón o un trapo en el desagüe del lavabo. Así evitas que caigan tornillos o piezas pequeñas mientras trabajas.",
      "title": "Tapa el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Retira la tapa decorativa de la manija con la punta del desarmador. Debe salir haciendo palanca suave; si no cede, envuélvela con un trapo para no rayarla.",
      "title": "Quita la tapa de la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Afloja el tornillo de la manija con el desarmador adecuado y sácalo. La manija debe quedar libre para retirarse sin forzarla.",
      "title": "Saca el tornillo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Levanta la manija del grifo y retírala del eje. Si está pegada, muévela de lado a lado con suavidad hasta que se suelte.",
      "title": "Retira la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Desenrosca la tuerca de retención o capuchón con la llave ajustable. Gira a la izquierda y usa un trapo para proteger el acabado del metal.",
      "title": "Afloja la tuerca de retención"
    },
    {
      "text": "Extrae el cartucho, vástago o arandela del interior del grifo. La pieza debe salir completa; si notas su posición, te ayudará al instalar la nueva.",
      "title": "Saca la pieza dañada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Compara la pieza vieja con el repuesto antes de instalarlo. Deben coincidir en tamaño, forma y puntos de ajuste; si no coinciden, no la coloques.",
      "title": "Verifica el repuesto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la pieza nueva en la misma posición que la anterior. Debe asentarse sin forzarla; si no entra bien, gira hasta alinearla correctamente.",
      "title": "Instala la pieza nueva"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enrosca de nuevo la tuerca de retención y apriétala firme, sin excederte. Debe quedar fija, pero no tan apretada que dañe la rosca.",
      "title": "Ajusta la tuerca"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vuelve a colocar la manija sobre el eje del grifo. Debe entrar recta y moverse con normalidad al girarla.",
      "title": "Reinstala la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inserta el tornillo de la manija y apriétalo hasta que quede seguro. La manija no debe tambalearse al moverla.",
      "title": "Aprieta el tornillo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Presiona la tapa decorativa en su lugar hasta que encaje. Debe quedar al ras y cubrir por completo el tornillo.",
      "title": "Coloca la tapa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre las válvulas de agua girándolas a la izquierda lentamente. Debes oír pasar el agua; si ves una fuga inmediata, ciérralas otra vez.",
      "title": "Restablece el agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cierra el grifo y observa la salida y la base durante un minuto. No debe gotear ni salir agua alrededor; si hay fuga, reajusta la pieza instalada.",
      "title": "Comprueba que ya no gotea"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Click **File** in the top-left corner of the window. A menu should open with options like Save and Save As.",
      "title": "Open the File menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Save**. If the document was already saved before, your changes are stored right away.",
      "title": "Click Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter a file name if a save window appears. Type the name into the **File name** field so you can find it later.",
      "title": "Type a file name"
    },
    {
      "text": "Choose the folder where you want to keep the document. You should see the selected location highlighted in the save window.",
      "title": "Select a save location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **Save** button in the save window. The window should close, and the document remains open.",
      "title": "Confirm the save"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the title bar at the top of the document window. The file name should appear there, confirming your work is saved.",
      "title": "Verify the document is saved"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place the case, motherboard, CPU, cooler, RAM, storage drive, GPU, power supply, screws, and a Phillips screwdriver on a clean table. You should be able to reach every part without moving away.",
      "title": "Gather the parts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open both side panels of the case by removing the thumbscrews or panel screws. Set the panels aside safely. You should have clear access to the inside of the case.",
      "title": "Open the case"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the motherboard flat on its box or anti-static foam. The board should sit stable with the CPU socket, RAM slots, and storage connectors easy to reach.",
      "title": "Set out the motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Release the CPU socket latch or retention arm on the motherboard. The socket cover should loosen or lift so the CPU can be placed without force.",
      "title": "Open the CPU socket"
